wiki_catalogs.name: Project Overview
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Create comprehensive content for this section focused on the MathHelper project. Explain its purpose as a web-based mathematical expression editor that enables users to visually manipulate algebraic expressions through interactive transformations. Describe the single-file architecture using vanilla JavaScript, HTML, and CSS, with no external dependencies. Highlight key capabilities such as expression parsing, visual block rendering, transformation rules, and branching history navigation. Provide a high-level summary of the user experience, from inputting expressions to exploring transformation paths. Use terminology consistent with the codebase, including references to Abstract Syntax Trees (AST), transformation rules, and immutability. Include a brief explanation of how the application supports learning and exploration of algebraic manipulation. This section should serve as an accessible entry point for new users and developers, setting the context for deeper dives into features and architecture.

wiki_catalogs.name: Expression Parsing
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Create detailed documentation for the ExpressionParser class in the MathHelper application. Explain how it converts string input into an Abstract Syntax Tree (AST) using recursive descent parsing. Detail the parsing order: handling additive operations after multiplicative, unary operators, and primary expressions. Describe support for implicit multiplication (e.g., 2a, ab) and operator precedence. Document error handling for invalid syntax like unmatched parentheses or consecutive operators. Include examples from the codebase showing how input strings like '2*(a+3)' are transformed into AST nodes. Explain the role of helper methods like peek(), consume(), isDigit(), and isLetter(). Address integration with the global state and how parsed expressions feed into the rendering system. Provide guidance on extending the parser with new operators or syntax.

wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed content for the Expression Visualization feature of the MathHelper application. Explain how mathematical expressions are parsed into Abstract Syntax Trees (AST) and rendered as interactive, color-coded blocks using the renderExpression and createExpressionElement functions from expression-editor.html. Detail the visual design including nested block structures, hover effects, and CSS-based color coding for different node types (operators, variables, constants, groups) as defined in the :root CSS variables. Describe the user interaction model where clicking a block triggers the context menu. Document the underlying data structure of expression nodes and their mapping to DOM elements. Address common issues like improper rendering due to invalid expressions and provide troubleshooting guidance. Explain customization options through CSS variables for theming and styling. Ensure the content is accessible to beginners while providing technical depth for developers extending the visualization system.

wiki_overview.content:
<blog>
# Comprehensive Project Analysis: Logical Expression Editor

## 1. Project Introduction

### Purpose Statement
The Logical Expression Editor is a web-based mathematical expression editor that enables users to visualize and manipulate algebraic expressions through interactive, color-coded blocks. The application allows bidirectional transformation of expressions using algebraic rules, with support for branching history navigation and real-time visual feedback.

### Core Goals and Objectives
- Provide an intuitive interface for exploring algebraic transformations
- Visualize mathematical expressions as nested, color-coded blocks
- Enable bidirectional application of transformation rules (expand/factor, implicit/explicit)
- Support branching history to explore multiple transformation paths
- Offer immediate visual feedback on expression changes

### Target Audience
This tool is designed for students, educators, and mathematicians who want to explore algebraic manipulations in an interactive environment. It serves as an educational tool for understanding mathematical properties and transformations.

## 2. Technical Architecture

### Component Breakdown
The application follows a single-file architecture with three main components:

```mermaid
flowchart TD
    A[Input Parser] --> B[Expression Tree]
    B --> C[Visual Renderer]
    C --> D[User Interaction]
    D --> E[Transformation Engine]
    E --> F[History Manager]
    F --> C
    G[Context Menu] --> E
    H[Description Panel] --> E
```

### Design Patterns
The application implements several key design patterns:

- **Abstract Syntax Tree (AST)**: Expressions are parsed into tree structures for manipulation
- **Immutability**: Deep cloning ensures state consistency across transformations
- **Event-Driven Architecture**: User interactions trigger transformation workflows
- **Single Responsibility**: Each function handles a specific aspect of expression manipulation

### System Relationships
```mermaid
flowchart TD
    A[User Input] --> B[Expression Parser]
    B --> C[Expression Tree]
    C --> D[Visual Renderer]
    D --> E[Browser DOM]
    E --> F[User Interaction]
    F --> G[Context Menu]
    G --> H[Transformation Engine]
    H --> I[History Manager]
    I --> J[State Update]
    J --> C
    I --> K[History Panel]
    H --> L[Description Panel]
```

## 3. Key Implementation

### Main Entry Points
- **Primary Entry**: `expression-editor.html` - The standalone HTML file containing all application code
- **Initialization**: DOMContentLoaded event that sets up event listeners and initializes global state

### Core Modules
- **Expression Parser**: Converts string input to Abstract Syntax Tree
- **Visual Renderer**: Transforms AST nodes into interactive DOM elements
- **Transformation Engine**: Applies algebraic rules to expression trees
- **History Manager**: Maintains branching history of expression states

### Configuration Approach
The application uses a self-contained configuration approach with:
- CSS variables for theming and styling
- JavaScript constants for UI configuration
- Inline configuration within the HTML file

### External Dependencies
- **None**: The application is built with pure vanilla JavaScript and requires no external libraries or frameworks

### Integration Points
- **Browser DOM**: Direct manipulation of DOM elements for rendering
- **Event System**: Integration with browser event system for user interactions
- **Local Storage**: Potential integration point for session persistence (not yet implemented)

### Component Relationship Diagram
```mermaid
graph LR
    A[Input Panel] --> B[Expression Parser]
    B --> C[Expression Tree]
    C --> D[Visual Renderer]
    D --> E[Expression Viewer]
    E --> F[Context Menu]
    F --> G[Transformation Engine]
    G --> H[History Manager]
    H --> I[History Panel]
    G --> J[Description Panel]
    H --> C
```

## 4. Key Features

### Functionality Overview
The Logical Expression Editor provides a comprehensive set of features for manipulating mathematical expressions:

- Dual input method (text entry and visual builder)
- Visual block representation with color coding
- Context menu for transformation rules
- Bidirectional transformation rules
- Branching history navigation
- Real-time feedback with animated highlights
- Rule descriptions with before/after examples

### Implementation Highlights
- **Expression Parsing**: Recursive descent parser with proper operator precedence handling
- **Visual Feedback**: Animated highlighting of changed blocks using CSS animations
- **Branching History**: Tree-based history structure that preserves all transformation paths
- **Context Menu**: Position-aware menu that displays only applicable transformation rules

### Feature Architecture Diagram
```mermaid
stateDiagram-v2
    [*] --> InputState
    InputState --> Parsing: Build Expression
    Parsing --> ErrorState: Invalid Syntax
    Parsing --> VisualState: Valid Expression
    VisualState --> Transformation: Click Block
    Transformation --> ContextMenu: Show Rules
    ContextMenu --> ApplyRule: Select Rule
    ApplyRule --> UpdateState: Transform Expression
    UpdateState --> VisualState: Render Updated
    UpdateState --> HistoryState: Record State
    VisualState --> NavigateHistory: Click History
    NavigateHistory --> VisualState: Restore Expression
    HistoryState --> [*]: End
```

</blog>
